{"format":"tiptap/v1","updatedAt":"2026-06-21T17:15:57.506Z","doc":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Partial derivatives"},{"type":"text","text":" measure how a function with "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"multiple inputs"},{"type":"text","text":" changes when you adjust "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"one specific input"},{"type":"text","text":" while keeping all others fixed. They are the fundamental building blocks of gradients in machine learning, telling models exactly which parameter to tweak and by how much to reduce error."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What it is — Clear definition and intuition"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Mathematical definition:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For a function "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"f(x, y)"},{"type":"text","text":" with multiple variables, the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"partial derivative with respect to x"},{"type":"text","text":" is:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"∂f/∂x = lim(h→0) [f(x+h, y) - f(x, y)] / h"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Key notation"},{"type":"text","text":": The symbol "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"∂"},{"type":"text","text":" (called \"del\" or \"partial\") distinguishes partial derivatives from regular single-variable derivatives."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conceptual meaning:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"When a function has multiple inputs, a regular derivative is not enough.\nYou need to know how the output changes when you adjust ONE input while keeping all others fixed.\nThis is a partial derivative [web:161]."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Simple rule"},{"type":"text","text":": "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Treat all other variables as constants"},{"type":"text","text":" and differentiate normally."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Geometric interpretation:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"For f(x, y), the partial derivative ∂f/∂x at a point is the SLOPE of the surface in the x-direction.\n\nIt's what you get if you \"slice\" the 3D surface with a plane parallel to the x-axis [web:161]:\n\n       z\n       |\n       |     / ← Surface z = f(x, y)\n       |    /\n       |___/______ x\n      /\n     y\n\n∂f/∂x: Move only in x (y stays fixed) → slope in x-direction\n∂f/∂y: Move only in y (x stays fixed) → slope in y-direction"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Analogy"},{"type":"text","text":": Standing on a hill, if you only move east (x-direction) while staying at the same latitude (y fixed), the slope you feel is ∂f/∂x."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Why it matters — Importance in Generative AI"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Partial derivatives are "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"essential for optimizing ML models"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ML Application"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"How partial derivatives apply"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Gradient Descent"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Each partial ∂L/∂wᵢ tells how loss changes when weight wᵢ changes"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Backpropagation"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Compute partial derivatives layer-by-layer through neural network"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Feature Selection"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"∂output/∂feature measures feature importance"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Hyperparameter Optimization"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"∂validation_loss/∂hyperparameter guides tuning"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Regularization"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Partial derivatives of penalty terms (L1/L2)"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Real example"},{"type":"text","text":": In training a neural network with 1 million weights, each partial derivative ∂Loss/∂wᵢ answers: \"If I increase this one weight by a tiny amount while keeping everything else the same, does the loss go up or down, and by how much?\""}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Benefits — Key advantages"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Isolate sensitivity"},{"type":"text","text":": Measure how sensitive output is to ONE parameter"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Multi-variable optimization"},{"type":"text","text":": Handle functions with many inputs"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Gradient construction"},{"type":"text","text":": Build gradient vector from partial derivatives"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Efficient updates"},{"type":"text","text":": Know exactly which parameter to change"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Trade-offs — Downsides and limitations"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Trade-off"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Impact"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Only local"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Partial derivatives measure change at one point only"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Assumes independence"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Treats other variables as constant (may not reflect reality)"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Computational cost"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Computing all partials for millions of parameters is expensive"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Non-differentiable points"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Some functions have undefined partial derivatives"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"How it works — Step-by-step computation"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Rule 1: Treat other variables as constants"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"f(x, y) = x² + xy + y³\n\n# Partial derivative w.r.t. x (hold y constant):\n∂f/∂x = 2x + y + 0  = 2x + y\n#   ↑    ↑    ↑\n#   x²   xy   y³ (treat as constant → derivative = 0)\n\n# Partial derivative w.r.t. y (hold x constant):\n∂f/∂y = 0 + x + 3y² = x + 3y²\n#       ↑    ↑     ↑\n#      x²   xy    y³"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Why it works"},{"type":"text","text":": When y is constant, the derivative of y³ is 0 (like derivative of constant 5 is 0)"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Example 1: Simple polynomial"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"f(x, y) = 3x² + 2y\n\n∂f/∂x = 6x  (derivative of 3x², treat 2y as constant → 0)\n∂f/∂y = 2   (derivative of 2y, treat 3x² as constant → 0)"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Example 2: Neural network loss"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Loss: L(w1, w2) = (w1*x1 + w2*x2 - y)²\n# where x1, x2, y are fixed inputs/target\n\n# Partial w.r.t. w1:\n∂L/∂w1 = 2(w1*x1 + w2*x2 - y) × x1\n#         ↑ prediction error       ↑ chain rule (derivative of inner)\n\n# Partial w.r.t. w2:\n∂L/∂w2 = 2(w1*x1 + w2*x2 - y) × x2"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Example 3: Complex function"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"f(x, y, z) = x²y + sin(z) + xyz\n\n# Partial w.r.t. x:\n∂f/∂x = 2xy + 0 + yz = 2xy + yz\n#       ↑    ↑   ↑\n#      x²y  sin(z) xyz\n\n# Partial w.r.t. y:\n∂f/∂y = x² + 0 + xz = x² + xz\n\n# Partial w.r.t. z:\n∂f/∂z = 0 + cos(z) + xy = cos(z) + xy"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Python implementations"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"SymPy (symbolic):"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import sympy as sp\n\nx, y, z = sp.symbols('x y z')\nf = x**2 + x*y + y**3\n\n# Partial derivatives\ndf_dx = sp.diff(f, x)  # 2*x + y\ndf_dy = sp.diff(f, y)  # x + 3*y**2\n\nprint(f\"∂f/∂x = {df_dx}\")\nprint(f\"∂f/∂y = {df_dy}\")"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"NumPy (numerical approximation):"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import numpy as np\n\ndef f(x, y):\n    return x**2 + x*y + y**3\n\n# Partial derivative w.r.t. x at point (1, 2)\nh = 1e-5\ndf_dx = (f(1 + h, 2) - f(1, 2)) / h  # ≈ 4\n\n# Partial derivative w.r.t. y at point (1, 2)\ndf_dy = (f(1, 2 + h) - f(1, 2)) / h  # ≈ 13\n\nprint(f\"∂f/∂x ≈ {df_dx}\")  # ≈ 4 (exact: 2x + y = 2×1 + 2 = 4)\nprint(f\"∂f/∂y ≈ {df_dy}\")  # ≈ 13 (exact: x + 3y² = 1 + 3×4 = 13)"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"PyTorch (autograd):"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import torch\n\nx = torch.tensor(1.0, requires_grad=True)\ny = torch.tensor(2.0, requires_grad=True)\n\nz = x**2 + x*y + y**3\n\n# Compute gradients\nz.backward()\n\nprint(f\"∂z/∂x = {x.grad}\")  # 4.0\nprint(f\"∂z/∂y = {y.grad}\")  # 13.0"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key relationships — Connecting concepts"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Partial derivative → Gradient:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"∇f = (∂f/∂x, ∂f/∂y, ∂f/∂z, ...)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"The gradient is just a vector of all partial derivatives"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"In ML:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Gradient of loss L w.r.t. weights w:\n∇L = (∂L/∂w₁, ∂L/∂w₂, ∂L/∂w₃, ..., ∂L/∂wₙ)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Each partial derivative tells the model: \"How does loss change if I tweak THIS weight while keeping all others fixed?\""}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Chain rule with partial derivatives:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"For f(g(x, y), h(x, y)):\n∂f/∂x = ∂f/∂g × ∂g/∂x + ∂f/∂h × ∂h/∂x  (multivariable chain rule)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"In backpropagation"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"∂Loss/∂w = ∂Loss/∂output × ∂output/∂activation × ∂activation/∂w"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"When to use it — Scenarios and decision criteria"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use partial derivatives when:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Multi-parameter function"},{"type":"text","text":": Loss function with many weights"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Gradient computation"},{"type":"text","text":": Need to build gradient vector"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sensitivity analysis"},{"type":"text","text":": Measure parameter importance"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"✅ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Optimization"},{"type":"text","text":": Minimize loss via gradient descent"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use regular derivative when:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"❌ "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Single variable"},{"type":"text","text":": Function has only one input (f(x))"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Common mistakes — Pitfalls to avoid"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Mistake"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Correction"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Not treating others as constant"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Always hold other variables fixed when computing ∂f/∂x"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Confusing with total derivative"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Partial = one variable changes; Total = all variables can change"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Ignoring chain rule"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use chain rule for composed functions (backpropagation)"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Manual computation"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use autograd (PyTorch/TensorFlow) for neural networks"}]}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Best practices — Proven approaches"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"1. Use autograd frameworks"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"import torch\n\nx = torch.tensor([1.0, 2.0, 3.0], requires_grad=True)\ny = x**2 + 3*x  # Multi-parameter function\ny.backward()\n\nprint(f\"Gradients: {x.grad}\")  # [2, 5, 8] = all partials"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2. Compute all partials for gradient"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Gradient = vector of all partial derivatives\ngradient = np.array([grad_w1, grad_w2, grad_w3, ...])"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"3. Visualize with 3D plots"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Plot f(x, y) surface to see partial derivatives as slopes\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key takeaways"}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Partial derivative = sensitivity to ONE variable"},{"type":"text","text":": ∂f/∂x measures change when x varies, y fixed"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Treat others as constants"},{"type":"text","text":": Hold all other variables fixed"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Symbol ∂"},{"type":"text","text":": Called \"del\" or \"partial,\" distinguishes from regular derivative d"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Geometric meaning"},{"type":"text","text":": Slope of surface in one direction (slice parallel to axis)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Gradient = vector of partials"},{"type":"text","text":": ∇f = (∂f/∂x, ∂f/∂y,...)"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"In ML"},{"type":"text","text":": Each ∂L/∂wᵢ answers: \"How does loss change if I tweak weight wᵢ while keeping others same?\""}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Chain rule"},{"type":"text","text":": Used in backpropagation for composed functions"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Essential for optimization"},{"type":"text","text":": Gradient descent uses partials to update weights"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Feature importance"},{"type":"text","text":": ∂output/∂feature measures sensitivity"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Use autograd"},{"type":"text","text":": PyTorch computes all partials automatically"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For Generative AI, partial derivatives are the building blocks of everything: each weight update in training, each backpropagation step, and each optimization algorithm relies on computing partial derivatives to determine precisely how each parameter affects the loss."}]}]}}
